# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: jim-devlin
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:jim-devlin/1873-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1873 throughout the world.
[src:jim-devlin/1874-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1874 throughout the world.
[src:jim-devlin/1875-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1875 throughout the world.
[src:jim-devlin/1876-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1876 throughout the world.
[src:jim-devlin/1876-in-baseball] After a tumultuous five-year existence, the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players (NA) folded following the 1875 season.
[src:jim-devlin/1876-in-baseball] One of the new rules put into place by the new league was that all teams had to be located in cities that had a population of 75,000 or more.
[src:jim-devlin/1876-in-baseball] The initial NL season began with eight teams, and they were asked to play seventy games between April 22 and October 21.
[src:jim-devlin/1876-in-baseball] The NL is often considered to be the first "major league", although it has been argued that the NA can make that claim.
[src:jim-devlin/1877-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1877 throughout the world.
[src:jim-devlin/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] The **1877 Louisville Grays scandal** was an incident in which members of the Louisville Grays baseball team accepted money to lose games.
[src:jim-devlin/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Four players – Bill Craver, Jim Devlin, George Hall and Al Nichols – were subsequently banned from professional baseball for life.
[src:jim-devlin/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] In the early days of professional baseball, crooked play was not uncommon, and many players were suspected of throwing games in exchange for money.
[src:jim-devlin/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Illegal influence by gamblers had undermined the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players (NA) in the early 1870s, and William Hulbert formed the National League (NL) in 1876 with the intention of driving it out of the game.
[src:jim-devlin/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Nevertheless, there were still several gambling-related scandals during the 1876 season.
[src:jim-devlin/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Jim Devlin started his baseball career in 1873 and was the Louisville Grays' pitcher in 1876 and 1877.
[src:jim-devlin/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] In 1876 he had a win–loss record of 30–35 and an earned run average of 1.56, while leading the league in complete games, innings pitched and strikeouts.
[src:jim-devlin/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] In 1877, Devlin went 35–25 with a 2.25 ERA and again led the league in complete games and innings pitched.
[src:jim-devlin/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] He started and completed each of the Grays' 61 games, an accomplishment no other pitcher in history has matched.
[src:jim-devlin/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Outfielder George Hall was one of the best sluggers in the game's early history.
[src:jim-devlin/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] After playing in the NA from 1871 to 1875, he joined the Philadelphia Athletics in 1876.
[src:jim-devlin/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] That season, he led the league with five home runs and finished second in batting average, on-base percentage, slugging percentage and total bases.
[src:jim-devlin/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] In 1877, he played for the Grays and had a .323 batting average.
[src:jim-devlin/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Shortstop Bill Craver was a noted crooked player who had been expelled from a previous team for throwing games in 1870.
[src:jim-devlin/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] He played for the New York Mutuals in 1876 before joining the Grays the following season.
[src:jim-devlin/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Al Nichols also played for the Mutuals in 1876.
[src:jim-devlin/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] He joined the Grays in the middle of the 1877 season on the recommendation of Hall and appeared in six games for the team.
[src:jim-devlin/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Newspapers named the players "Terror" Devlin, "Gentleman George" Hall, "Butcher" Craver and "Slippery Elm" Nichols".
[src:jim-devlin/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] After the games of August 13, 1877, the Grays were in first place by four games over St.
[src:jim-devlin/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Louis and 4.5 over the Boston Red Caps, with a record of 27 wins and 13 losses, and with some 20 games left to play.
[src:jim-devlin/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] They then commenced a nine-game winless streak (including one tie) and eventually lost the championship to Boston.
[src:jim-devlin/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] They won six out of their last seven, making their season record of 35-25 look reasonably respectable, but those wins came after Boston had clinched the pennant, having won 20 of their final 21 games.
[src:jim-devlin/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Louisville finished second, seven games behind Boston.
[src:jim-devlin/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Chase received telegrams informing him of suspicious gambling activity involving the team.
[src:jim-devlin/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] He started an investigation, and Devlin and Hall confessed to throwing several exhibition games late in the season, with Devlin receiving up to $100 per game.
[src:jim-devlin/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] On October 4, the entire team was gathered, and Chase demanded that they turn over their telegrams.
[src:jim-devlin/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Every player except Craver complied, and the telegrams showed that Devlin, Hall and Nichols had thrown games.
[src:jim-devlin/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] On October 30, Craver, Devlin, Hall and Nichols were expelled from the club, and on December 4, the NL banned them from professional baseball for the rest of their lives.
[src:jim-devlin/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] The Grays franchise folded after the 1877 season.
[src:jim-devlin/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Over the next few decades, there were fewer suspicions of game-fixing in professional baseball.
[src:jim-devlin/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] The four banned players were never reinstated.
[src:jim-devlin/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Nichols played semi-professional baseball, Craver and Devlin became police officers, and Hall worked as an engraver and clerk.
[src:jim-devlin/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Devlin tried to be reinstated many times but was unsuccessful.
[src:jim-devlin/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] In one instance, he got on his knees and begged Hulbert for another chance.
[src:jim-devlin/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Hulbert responded by handing him $50 (roughly equivalent to $1,200 in 2017 value) and saying, "Devlin, that's what I think of you personally; but, damn you, you have sold a game; you are dishonest and this National League will not stand for it." Devlin died of tuberculosis in 1883.
[src:jim-devlin/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] His 1.90 career ERA is the third-lowest of all-time among pitchers with at least 1,000 innings pitched.
[src:jim-devlin/aaron-harang] Harang graduated from Patrick Henry High School, then went on to San Diego State University.
[src:jim-devlin/aaron-harang] He was first drafted by the Boston Red Sox in the 22nd round of the 1996 amateur draft, but did not sign with the team.
[src:jim-devlin/aaron-harang] In 1998, he played collegiate summer baseball with the Cotuit Kettleers of the Cape Cod Baseball League.
[src:jim-devlin/aaron-harang] After college, Harang was drafted by the Texas Rangers in the 6th round of the 1999 draft and signed with them.
[src:jim-devlin/aaron-harang] He played for the rookie-level Pulaski Rangers in 1999, finishing with a 9–2 record and 2.30 ERA in 16 appearances (10 starts), including one complete game shutout.
[src:jim-devlin/aaron-harang] He was selected as the Appalachian League Pitcher of the Year and made the postseason all-star team.
[src:jim-devlin/aaron-harang] In 2000, with the Charlotte Rangers, he was 13–5 with a 3.32 ERA in 27 starts and was selected as a Florida State League All-Star.
[src:jim-devlin/aaron-harang] In 2000, Harang was traded with minor leaguer Ryan Cullen to the Oakland Athletics for Randy Velarde.
[src:jim-devlin/aaron-harang] He played with the AA Midland RockHounds in 2001, starting 27 games with a 10–8 record and 4.14 ERA.
[src:jim-devlin/aaron-harang] Harang made his Major League debut for the Athletics on May 25, 2002, against the Tampa Bay Devil Rays.
[src:jim-devlin/aaron-harang] He pitched seven shutout innings in his debut, with 10 strikeouts, to record the win.
[src:jim-devlin/aaron-harang] He started 15 games for the team that season, and also made 1 relief appearance.
[src:jim-devlin/aaron-harang] In 2003, he started 6 games, with a 1–3 record and 5.34 ERA.
[src:jim-devlin/aaron-harang] During the 2003 season, Harang was traded to the Reds with Joe Valentine and minor leaguer Jeff Bruksch for José Guillén.
[src:jim-devlin/aaron-harang] In 2004, he went 10–9 with a 4.83 ERA for the Reds.
[src:jim-devlin/aaron-harang] In 2005, Harang led the Reds with 11 wins, 211+2⁄3 innings pitched, 163 strikeouts, and 19 quality starts.
[src:jim-devlin/aaron-harang] He was the first Reds pitcher to pitch 200 innings in a season since Elmer Dessens in 2001.
[src:jim-devlin/aaron-harang] He received votes for NL Pitcher of the Month in May after going 3–1 with 1.93 ERA over five starts.
[src:jim-devlin/aaron-harang] In 2006, Harang started on Opening Day for the Reds on April 3 against the Chicago Cubs and allowed 9 runs (6 earned) over 5 innings.
[src:jim-devlin/aaron-harang] In his third start of the season, Harang pitched 7 shutout innings against the St.
[src:jim-devlin/aaron-harang] Louis Cardinals, facing off against reigning Cy Young Award winner Chris Carpenter.
[src:jim-devlin/aaron-harang] Harang allowed 4 hits and got 4 strikeouts, also driving in the only run of the game as the Reds won 1–0.
[src:jim-devlin/aaron-harang] Harang pitched a complete game shutout against the Milwaukee Brewers on April 23, allowing five hits as the Reds won 11–0.
[src:jim-devlin/aaron-harang] Harang led the National League in 2006 with 6 complete games and 216 strikeouts, topping Jake Peavy by only 1 strikeout.
[src:jim-devlin/aaron-harang] He also tied for the league lead with 16 wins and 35 starts.
[src:jim-devlin/aaron-harang] However, he received no votes for the Cy Young Award, won by Brandon Webb.
[src:jim-devlin/aaron-harang] Harang was the 11th National League pitcher since 1956 to lead the National League in both wins and strikeouts, with all other league leaders also winning the Cy Young Award.
[src:jim-devlin/aaron-harang] On February 6, 2007, Harang signed a four-year, $36.5 million contract extension with the Reds.
[src:jim-devlin/aaron-harang] On July 23, he pitched 10 innings, throwing 121 pitches, becoming the first Reds pitcher to pitch 10 innings since 1989.
[src:jim-devlin/aaron-harang] However, he received a no-decision because the Reds did not win the game until the 12th inning.
[src:jim-devlin/aaron-harang] On September 3, he became the victim of the 3,000th strikeout recorded by Pedro Martínez.
[src:jim-devlin/aaron-harang] Harang ended the season with an NL-leading 4.19 strikeout-to-walk ratio and tied for the lead with 12 wild pitches.
[src:jim-devlin/aaron-harang] In 2008, he led the majors in giving up 19 home runs at home.
[src:jim-devlin/aaron-harang] His homefield, Great American Ballpark, allow the second-most home runs that season.
[src:jim-devlin/aaron-harang] Harang hit his first career home run on July 24, 2009, a three-run shot to left field off of Randy Wells of the Cubs.
[src:jim-devlin/aaron-harang] However, Harang lost that game to Wells and the Cubs.
[src:jim-devlin/aaron-harang] He missed the end of the 2009 season after undergoing an emergency appendectomy in August.
[src:jim-devlin/aaron-harang] He ended the season with a 4.21 ERA, 1.41 WHIP and 6–14 record.
[src:jim-devlin/aaron-harang] In September 2010, Harang was removed from the starting rotation due to ineffectiveness and having been on the DL for two months due to back spasms.
[src:jim-devlin/aaron-harang] In a ceremonial "goodbye," he started the final game of the season against the Brewers, but exited in the third inning with a blister on his finger.
[src:jim-devlin/aaron-harang] Harang was left off the Reds 2010 playoff roster.
[src:jim-devlin/aaron-harang] On November 3, 2010, the Reds bought Harang out of his 2011 contract option, making him a free agent.
[src:jim-devlin/aaron-harang] On December 6, 2010, Harang signed a one-year, $3.5 million contract with the San Diego Padres that included a mutual option for 2012.
[src:jim-devlin/aaron-harang] On July 9, 2011, Harang had a no-hitter through six innings against the Los Angeles Dodgers but was pulled after walking 3 and throwing 95 pitches.
[src:jim-devlin/aaron-harang] He made 28 starts in 2011, with a 14–7 record and 3.64 ERA for the Padres.
[src:jim-devlin/aaron-harang] The team did not to pick up his 2012 option, making him a free agent.
[src:jim-devlin/aaron-harang] On December 8, 2011, Harang signed a 2-year, $12 million contract with the Los Angeles Dodgers, with a mutual option for 2014.
[src:jim-devlin/aaron-harang] On April 13, 2012, Harang struck out 9 consecutive batters after giving up a single to set the all time Dodgers record against the San Diego Padres.
[src:jim-devlin/aaron-harang] The record was previously held by Johnny Podres with 8 in 1962.
[src:jim-devlin/aaron-harang] The streak was stopped by Will Venable when he hit an opposite-field home run.
[src:jim-devlin/aaron-harang] Harang finished one strikeout short of tying Tom Seaver's Major League record of 10 consecutive strikeouts in 1970 and tied his career high with 13 total strikeouts in the game.
[src:jim-devlin/aaron-harang] On June 7, Harang allowed 3 runs in 6 innings in an 8–3 victory over the Philadelphia Phillies to collect his 100th career Major League win.
[src:jim-devlin/aaron-harang] In 31 starts for the Dodgers in 2012, he finished 10–10 with a 3.61 ERA.
[src:jim-devlin/aaron-harang] On April 6, 2013, the Dodgers traded Harang and $4.25 million to cover part of his salary to the Colorado Rockies for catcher Ramón Hernández.
[src:jim-devlin/aaron-harang] The Rockies designated Harang for assignment and on April 11 traded him and cash to the Seattle Mariners for minor leaguer Steven Hensley.
[src:jim-devlin/aaron-harang] Harang pitched shutouts on May 27 and June 11, tying him for second in MLB in shutouts in 2013.
[src:jim-devlin/aaron-harang] In 22 starts for Seattle, he was 5–11 with a 5.76 ERA.
[src:jim-devlin/aaron-harang] He was designated for assignment on August 26 and released on September 1.
[src:jim-devlin/aaron-harang] On September 2, 2013, Harang signed a minor league contract with the New York Mets and assigned to the Triple-A Las Vegas 51s.
[src:jim-devlin/aaron-harang] Harang joined the Mets on September 12 and was generally effective for the last few weeks of the season.
[src:jim-devlin/aaron-harang] While he was 0–1 with the Mets, he had a 3.52 ERA and struck out 26 batters in 23 innings pitched.
[src:jim-devlin/aaron-harang] He became a free agent after the season.
[src:jim-devlin/aaron-harang] On February 15, 2014, Harang signed a minor league contract with the Cleveland Indians.
[src:jim-devlin/aaron-harang] On March 24, he was released by the Indians and signed a one-year major league contract with the Atlanta Braves.
[src:jim-devlin/aaron-harang] After his first four starts with the Braves, Harang posted a 0.70 ERA, the lowest in the National League.
[src:jim-devlin/aaron-harang] After his next start, he became the first pitcher since Pedro Martínez in 1997 to start a season with five starts of at least 6 innings and one or fewer runs allowed.
[src:jim-devlin/aaron-harang] He only had six such starts in the rest of his 28 starts, with a 4.07 ERA after his hot start.
[src:jim-devlin/aaron-harang] He finished the year with a 12–12 record and a 3.57 ERA over 33 starts.
[src:jim-devlin/aaron-harang] He was ninth in the National League with 2041⁄3 innings pitched and was also in the top 10 in hits, walks, and wild pitches.
[src:jim-devlin/aaron-harang] On January 5, 2015, Harang signed a one-year, $5 million contract with Philadelphia Phillies that included performance bonuses.
[src:jim-devlin/aaron-harang] He again started strong, with a 1.82 ERA in his first nine starts.
[src:jim-devlin/aaron-harang] After missing most of July with plantar fasciitis in his left foot, Harang ended his final MLB season with a 6–15 record and 4.86 ERA in 29 starts for the Phillies.
[src:jim-devlin/aaron-harang] He had the lowest percentage pulled against him, 31.7 percent, among major league pitchers.
[src:jim-devlin/aaron-harang] He also was the 11th best pitcher at inducing infield fly balls.
[src:jim-devlin/aaron-harang] Harang became a free agent on November 2.
[src:jim-devlin/aaron-harang] In March 2016, he said he was not planning to pitch that year but could change his mind.
[src:jim-devlin/aaron-harang] He did not sign another contract with an MLB team.
[src:jim-devlin/aaron-harang] He had a four-seam fastball and two-seam fastball averaging about 90–94 miles per hour.
[src:jim-devlin/aaron-harang] He also threw a slider and changeup in the low 80s and a curveball in the low-to-mid 70s, as well as a small handful of cutters.
[src:jim-devlin/aaron-harang] Harang mostly used his four-seamer and slider against right-handed hitters, while using more variety with left-handed hitters.
[src:jim-devlin/aaron-harang] His curve was typically used early in the count, often against lefties.
[src:jim-devlin/aaron-harang] Harang married Jennifer Wade in 2002 and has three children, Addison, Kailey, and Dustin.
[src:jim-devlin/aaron-harang] Harang's younger brother Darryl pitched in the minor leagues for the Toronto Blue Jays organization from 2004 to 2008 and in the Reds system in 2010.
[src:jim-devlin/aaron-harang] During his playing career, Harang gave tickets to military families in a program called "Aaron's Aces." Harang also gave Reds clubhouse staff an 8-person golf cart in 2009.
[src:jim-devlin/jim-devlin] Jim Devlin began his career in the first organized professional league, the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players (NA), as an infielder for his hometown Philadelphia White Stockings in 1873, and the Chicago White Stockings in the 1874 and 1875 seasons.
[src:jim-devlin/jim-devlin] In 1876, the NA folded and was replaced by the National League (NL) that lives on to this day.
[src:jim-devlin/jim-devlin] In this year, Devlin began pitching for the Louisville Grays, starting 68 games with an impeccable 1.56 earned run average and leading the Grays in batting with .315.
[src:jim-devlin/jim-devlin] Devlin's best pitch was a "drop pitch", now known as a sinker, which he may have been the first to throw.
[src:jim-devlin/jim-devlin] In 1877, Devlin, the only pitcher on the roster, threw every pitch of his team's 61 games, the only pitcher ever to do so.
[src:jim-devlin/jim-devlin] Led by Devlin and slugger George Hall, the Grays opened up a four-game lead in the NL pennant race by mid-August.
[src:jim-devlin/jim-devlin] However, the Grays suffered a horrendous road trip and endured a seven-game losing streak, which was characterized by uncharacteristic "bonehead" plays and poor pitching.
[src:jim-devlin/jim-devlin] The Grays relinquished their lead and eventually finished second, seven games behind the Boston Red Caps (who subsequently won 20 of 21 games to end the season).
[src:jim-devlin/jim-devlin] Meanwhile, certain Grays were seen around town wearing fancy new jewelry and ostentatiously dining at exclusive restaurants.
[src:jim-devlin/jim-devlin] At the end of the season, suspicion arose that Grays players were being paid to intentionally lose games.
[src:jim-devlin/jim-devlin] This suspicion increased as the players performed very well in postseason exhibition matches.
[src:jim-devlin/jim-devlin] Furthermore, the *Louisville Courier-Journal* discovered that utility infielder Al Nichols had received an abnormally high number of telegrams.
[src:jim-devlin/jim-devlin] *Courier-Journal* writer John Haldeman, who was the son of the Grays' president and who sometimes played second base in the team's exhibition games, was the first to publicly accuse the Grays of throwing games.
[src:jim-devlin/jim-devlin] Team vice president Charles Chase, who had earlier received but disregarded telegrams informing him that gamblers were betting against the Grays in certain games, began an investigation.
[src:jim-devlin/jim-devlin] Devlin and Hall confessed, and Chase demanded that his players allow him to inspect their telegrams.
[src:jim-devlin/jim-devlin] The telegrams confirmed that Nichols was coordinating the games with New York City gamblers.
[src:jim-devlin/jim-devlin] Bill Craver, the team's shortstop, who was the only player to deny the request and who carried a bad reputation from his days in the National Association, was presumed guilty by association and was suspended.
[src:jim-devlin/jim-devlin] NL president William Hulbert decided to make a stand against gambling.
[src:jim-devlin/jim-devlin] He immediately banned Devlin, Hall, Nichols and Craver from the league for life.
[src:jim-devlin/jim-devlin] Craver, against whom no evidence of gambling was ever found but had refused to comply with the investigation, was outraged and appealed the suspension.
[src:jim-devlin/jim-devlin] Devlin also appealed to the NL for reinstatement every year for the rest of his life.
[src:jim-devlin/jim-devlin] Devlin even appealed to Harry Wright, one of the game's most influential figures, for help in reinstating him, but Wright never responded to Devlin's requests.
[src:jim-devlin/jim-devlin] Devlin, who found work in Philadelphia as a police officer, died poor of tuberculosis in 1883 and was survived by a wife and son.
[src:jim-devlin/jim-devlin] He is interred at New Cathedral Cemetery in Philadelphia.
